Course-1: Python for Data Systems (Project): FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 40

Project Overview:¶

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost_of_the_order: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Question 1: Write the code to scrape the table from the 'foodhub_order.html' and read the data. (0.5 mark)¶

In [82]:
with open('foodhub_orders.html') as f:
    soup = BeautifulSoup(f, 'html.parser')

# Identify the column names for the future dataframe
column_titles = soup.find_all('th')
column_names = []
for col in column_titles:
    column_names.append(col.text)

# Now extract the data that is associated with each column from the tbody
combined_data = []
data = soup.find('tbody').find_all('tr')
for i in range(len(data)):
    data_lst = data[i].text.strip().split('\n')
    combined_data.append(data_lst)
    
# Create a pandas dataframe, initial view of the data
df = pd.DataFrame(combined_data, columns=column_names)

print('##### DataFrame Head ####')
print(df.head())

Research the ratings field to seek solutions for nan values¶

In [87]:
raw_data = df.copy()
# See if the restaurants have other columns with non-nan that we can replace by average
df_test = df.groupby('restaurant_name')['rating'].mean().reset_index().sort_values('rating')
# From this I've learned that there are restaurants that have all nan regarding ratings, non with a zero avg otherwise
df_zero_avg = df_test[df_test.rating==0]
# Replace nan with restaurant avg to corret as many as possible
df["rating"] = df.groupby("restaurant_name")['rating'].transform(lambda x: x.fillna(x.mean()))

Question 14: Suppose the company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants. The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4. Write the code to find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer. (2 marks)¶

In [110]:
# Generate a secondary dataframe with the count of reviews, and average - grouped by restaurant
# Utilzing the raw_data set because it doesn't have the fill na logic included
promotional_df = raw_data[raw_data['rating'].notnull()].groupby('restaurant_name').agg(
    {'order_id': 'count', 'rating': 'mean'}).reset_index()
# Rename the columns to make logical sense
promotional_df.rename(columns={'order_id':'order_cnt', 'rating':'avg_rating'}, inplace=True)
# Filter the data for the requested criteria
promotional_df = promotional_df[(promotional_df['order_cnt']>50)&(promotional_df['avg_rating']>4)]
# Sort the values for "ranking"
promotional_df.sort_values(['avg_rating', 'order_cnt'], ascending=False, inplace=True)
promotional_df['restaurant_name'].to_list()

Question 15: Suppose the company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Write the code to find the net revenue generated on all the orders given in the dataset. (2 marks)¶

In [111]:
# Delivery charge calculation for company FoodHub
# Although not specified for orders less than or equal to $5, the revenue is assumed $0 and applied for those 9 orders
conditions = [df['cost_of_the_order']>20, df['cost_of_the_order']>5, df['cost_of_the_order']<5]
values = [df['cost_of_the_order']*.25, df['cost_of_the_order']*.15, 0]
df['company_revenue'] = np.select(conditions, values)
# Calculate net revenue
revenue = round(df['company_revenue'].sum(), 2)

print(f'The revenue for FoodHub in the dataset is: ${revenue}')

The revenue for FoodHub in the dataset is: $6166.3

Observations:¶

Under these conditions the revenue realized by FoodHub in this dataset is \$6,166.30 <br> However, this comes with a disclaimer that the 9 orders sub-\\$5.01 were assumed to be \$0 revenue as it wasn't specified in the conditions.

I recommend setting a minimum delivery charge to prevent these occurrences.

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 18: Write the conclusions and business recommendations derived from the analysis. (3 marks)¶

Conclusion:¶

My recommendation for FoodHub is to target the following restaurants for the promotional advertisement campaign. They are both on the Top 15 Restaurants list (volume based), and meet the minimum ratings and orders with ratings criteria.

The Meatball Shop
Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken
Shake Shack
RedFarm Broadway
Blue Ribbon Sushi
RedFarm Hudson
Parm

With that being said, I believe it would be of value to alter the ratings program. We need to focus on driving a behavior of reviewing the experience, and potentially altering the rating scale. We have 736 of 1898 orders that didn't review/rate. That is only 61% or the customer base. A program that incentivizes the reviewing/rating process would provide more data and increased accuracy. I also think we should increase the scale to a 10-point scale allowing people to be a little more precise in their rating. We see a fairly even spread for ratings of 3, 4, and 5. Too small of a scale to support actionable results.

We need to consider a minimum fee or something to make up for the orders less than $5. Current model seems to deliver those meals for no charge.

Lastly, I recommend that we consider an upcharge for weekday deliverys. We have much fewer orders on the weekdays, but order delivery time has a 26\% increase. I assume this is due to traffic during busier times of the day. Possibly upcharge during the primetime, and reduce costs outside of that time, but near, to help people receive their meals faster, and spread our business out over a greater time period.
